                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Z( \tau ) ^{\prime }Q_{\tilde{W}( \tau ) }Z( \tau ) =Z( \tau ) ^{\prime }Q_{W( \tau ) ^{( 1) }}Z( \tau ) $ \end{document}
                  . Using these facts, we can factor (A.20) into a product of (unnormalized) conditional and marginal probability density functions, each of which is either the density of a matrix‐variate normal distribution or that of an inverted Wishart distribution. Hence, on appropriate renormalization, we obtain the training sample posterior density given by expression (A.19). Q.E.D.

